      "name": "Construct stiffness QoI comparison — FEA vs. experimental (N=11)",
      "description": "Construct axial-bending stiffness predicted by the three-laboratory FEA ensemble was compared against N=11 physical test specimens under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending loading. Mean predicted stiffness was 187.4 N/mm versus experimental mean of 183.1 N/mm (2.3% difference). Normalised error metric E/uval = 0.74, well within the pre-specified acceptance threshold of 1.96. Mesh convergence had been demonstrated at 3.1% energy-norm change between refinement levels; material properties were drawn from certified titanium alloy coupon data supplied by DePuy Synthes. The simulation runs were executed in Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 on the FDA high-performance computing cluster; input decks and result archives are retained in the project repository under revision tag v1.4.2. Independent review of the FEA setup was performed by the University of Arkansas Computational Mechanics group prior to result extraction. All boundary conditions replicated the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry to within 0.05 mm tolerance. This result constitutes the primary quantitative evidence supporting the credibility claim.",
